PhD thesis- IRT SystemX / LIP6 - University Pierre & Marie Curie

Information Diffusion in Social Networks

Duration: 3 years=20
Start: as soon as possible=20

Topic

Analyzing and understanding the information flows produced by social media =
sites has become a major issue for many actors. These sites provide access =
to information at an unprecedented scale allowing to follow worldwide event=
s and to cope with unexpected events. For companies, social media are often=
 a key component for marketing through the following of product adoption, t=
he improvement of brand reputation or the targeting of populations. Going o=
ne step further, organizations and companies have started using these media=
 for influencing their audience and customers which gave rise to the emergi=
ng business of social media monitoring. From an industrial
perspective, modeling and monitoring tools are limited to web analytics. On=
 the academic side, despite an increasing number of publications on social =
media, we are far from covering the complexity and diversity of actual situ=
ations.=20

The study of propagation models first appeared in social science, epidemiol=
ogy and marketing. The development of social media and the availability of =
massive amounts of data then offered an unprecedented opportunity for new d=
evelopments in computer science and data analysis. Current propagation mode=
ls generally start from a known diffusion network and aim at reproducing ob=
served diffusion phenomena or predict future diffusion (Gome=E2=80=90Rodrig=
uez 11, Saito 08, Yang 10). They are generally based on a series of assumpt=
ions: 1) the world is =E2=80=9Cclosed=E2=80=9D (only
 one networks is considered at a time, diffusion occurs only through the ne=
twork links, there is no interference with the outside world and the networ=
k is fully known), 2) each information spreads in isolation and does not in=
terfere with others 3) information is generic and follows the same law over=
 the whole network (diffusion does not depend on the content of the message=
s or on the thematic preferences of users), 4) the network is static. Such =
hypotheses are over=E2=80=90simplistic. In real networks, information flows
through multiple channels and media and the observed data only provide a pa=
rtial view of the informational context of the users. Diffusion of informat=
ion also depends heavily on the content of the messages and on users=E2=80=
=99 profile. Networks are constantly evolving. Finally, one is often intere=
sted into following information on a series of social media and not only on=
 a specific one. We propose in this PHD thesis to explore new models to ove=
rcome these identified limits.
=C2=A0

Context


This PhD will mainly take place at SystemX (Plateau de Saclay, Palaiseau)=
=C2=A0and partly within the MLIA team of the LIP6 (Paris). It will be co-su=
pervised by Patrick Gallinari and Sylvain Lamprier from LIP6 - UPMC. The PH=
D thesis is fully funded for a period of three years.
=C2=A0
Contacts=20


Patrick Gallinari : patrick.gallinari@lip6.fr
Sylvain Lamprier : sylvain.lamprier@lip6.fr=

